<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Bottomley defends stance on tobacco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, yesterday defended the
government's reluctance to impose a ban on tobacco advertising, in spite of
the publication of a government report which concludes advertising does have
a positive effect on consumption.
Mrs Bottomley told the commons select committee on health that the
government saw tobacco advertising as important, but a statutory ban was 'a
very serious step to take in a free country,' as it would have grave
implications for commercial freedom of speech.
She said the UK had already reduced the proportion of smokers from 45 per
cent of the population to 30 per cent, second only to the Netherlands in
Europe, and had set a target of 20 per cent in the Health of the Nation
white paper.
A range of measures would be deployed to reach that target, including
possible strengthening of the current voluntary arrangements limiting
tobacco advertising, and maintaining high prices for tobacco products.
Mrs Bottomley said Britain was attempting to persuade other EC countries of
the importance of pricing in reducing tobacco consumption.
</TEXT>
