<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Benefits freeze 'considered'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAPERS suggesting that ministers are considering freezing certain social
security benefits or uprating them by less than the rate of inflation were
published by Labour yesterday, as part of the opposition's pre-emptive
strike on the government's public spending plans.
The documents, released by Mr Donald Dewar, shadow social security
secretary, discuss the presentational difficulties for the government of
being tougher on those who are sick or disabled than on those who are able
to work.
The cabinet will today have its first opportunity to discuss the spending
plans drawn up by the public expenditure committee chaired by Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor. Ministers will be able to discuss the options
thoroughly, but are unlikely to make firm decisions until next week's
meeting.
Social security ministers insist that the Tories' manifesto commitments will
be met. In strict terms, these are limited to uprating child benefit and the
basic state pension in line with the rate of inflation.
Some benefits, such as invalidity benefit, currently have to be uprated in
line with inflation, though this link could be broken if the government
brought forward legislation to do so. Others merely have to be reviewed each
year, though the means-tested ones usually are raised.
The documents suggest that in his meetings with Treasury ministers Mr Peter
Lilley, the social security secretary, will want to point out the
presentational problems 'of benefit freezes affecting the poorest to raise
tax allowances for those in work'. Mr Dewar said that the papers, dated
around the end of last month, show that the question of benefit freezes had
been on the agenda, and called on Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to say
in advance of the Autumn Statement if the idea of under-indexing had been
discarded.
'It would be a political blunder, even by the standards of this chancellor,
to hit those on benefit - the sick and the unemployed - in an effort to bail
out the Treasury,' Mr Dewar said.
</TEXT>
