<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Extent of Euro rebellion hangs on
motion - David Owen takes soundings among those Conservative MPs who could
be crucial to the prime minister next Wednesday
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SCALE of Mr John Major's task in securing a Commons majority in next
week's vote on the Maastricht treaty was underlined last night by
indications that as many as 50 Conservative MPs are currently minded to
oppose the government. Telephone interviews with scores of Tory MPs suggest
that this level of opposition could conceivably materialise if the
government insists on tabling a substantive motion vowing to press ahead
with examination of the bill implementing the treaty without delay.
A revolt on this scale would leave the government staring defeat in the face
 -although past experience suggests the number is likely to be considerably
whittled down by the time the division bell rings.
Nevertheless, if the prime minister continues the confrontational route on
which he embarked this week, he will be relying heavily on his ability to
shepherd several of these potential rebels back to the fold.
The alternative is to bow to backbench pressure, either by tabling an
anodyne technical motion or agreeing to delay detailed consideration of the
Maastricht Bill.
If the motion which eventually appears is interpreted as a vote of
confidence in the government, the prospective rebellion would probably
evaporate almost to vanishing point.
As the government ponders tactics, those most likely to face the tender
mercies of the whips are the potential waverers: backbenchers who have
hedged their rebellious instincts.
Into this category fall Mr Paul Marland, MP for Gloucestershire West, Mr
Roger Moate, Faversham, Mr John Townend, Bridlington, Sir Rhodes Boyson,
Brent North, Mr Michael Lord, Suffolk Central, and others.
Some of this group indicated this week that a concession on timing could be
the key to securing their support for a substantive motion, although others
may be satisfied by the news of Denmark's attempt to break the impasse over
its ratification of the treaty.
Mr Townend said he would be 'unlikely to vote for' a substantive motion,
while Sir Rhodes said he would 'find it very difficult' to give the
government his support. Mr Lord said he would 'have to see what the wording
is'. He added: 'All I am interested in is: are they going to bring the bill
back. If they do, I shall vote against it.'
Among the group, Mr Moate - who abstained when the Maastricht Bill received
its second Commons reading - may prove the most intractable to sticks and
blandishments. 'At the very least I would abstain, but my inclination would
be to vote against,' he said.
Government business managers will take heart from their memories of fizzled
backbench rebellions of the recent past - notably in July when not one Tory
supported a Labour amendment to extend a moratorium on stamp duty on house
sales.
Indeed, there is already evidence that potential rebels are beginning to
back away from confrontation.
Mr Den Dover, MP for Chorley, yesterday said he would support the
government. On Tuesday, asked how he would react to a substantive motion
vowing to press on with the Maastricht treaty as quickly as possible, he
said he was 'inclined to vote against'. He said the switch was 'because of
the Danish position being clarified'.
Mr James Hill, MP for Southampton Test, also pledged this week to back the
government. A month ago he told the FT: 'If there is any thought of
bulldozing through the same thing again, they will find a lot of people like
me hesitating.'
He said in explanation: 'I suppose I have been reading a lot more about
Maastricht.'
It is clear that many implacable opponents of Maastricht are prepared to
back Mr Major next week, either out of personal ambition or because they are
unwilling to risk precipitating a situation in which the government could
fall.
One new MP said: 'I am crying out for this measure to be brought down but I
am not sure this is the right time to act. It is nothing short of insulting
to bring it forward now.' Another more experienced hand said: 'We are not in
the business of trying to get rid of the government.'
Mr Major, however, must be privately dismayed at the depth of the resolve of
experienced MPs like Mr Peter Griffiths, Portsmouth North, Mr Bill Walker,
Tayside North and Mr John Wilkinson, Ruislip-Northwood, all of whom were
adamant this week that they would oppose a substantive motion.
Mr Walker, who abstained on the bill's second reading, said: 'At the general
election, I stood on a platform that I would oppose Maastricht. I will not
let my constituents down.' Mr Wilkinson said: 'Her Majesty's government is
hell-bent on committing hara kiri.'
The prime minister must be even more concerned at the determination of newly
elected MPs like Mr Warren Hawksley, Halesowen and Stourbridge, and Mr
Walter Sweeney, Vale of Glamorgan, to oppose a substantive motion.
Mr Sweeney said: 'I am very sorry I did not vote against the government in
the second reading in May. I felt rather pusillanimous when the Danes voted
against (Maastricht) in their referendum.'
If the other hardliners keep their nerve, and the 22 Tory rebels from the
second reading remained opposed, a vote on a substantive motion would be
desperately close, even assuming the least determined of the 50 were brought
into line.
It cannot be presumed that all of the 22 would continue to defy the
leadership. In May they did so safe in the knowledge that Labour's
instruction to its MPs to abstain would ensure a convincing government
majority.
But none of them has yet publicly promised to back the government this time
around.
Sir Trevor Skeet, MP for Bedfordshire North - seen by some as a potential
waverer - said yesterday: 'On a substantive motion, I am against it, exactly
as I was last time . . . The prime minister does not require the vote at
all. This is very provocative.'
</TEXT>
