<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Loyalists step up their fightback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY loyalists and Euro-enthusiasts intensified their fightback against the
Euro-sceptics yesterday as they sensed that the tide of opinion at
Westminster was turning their way.
The campaign gained momentum, both behind the scenes and in front of the
cameras, as loyalists insisted that colleagues who had been prepared to vote
against the government were being won over by the argument that to do so
would reduce Mr John Major's chances of securing a successful outcome to the
Edinburgh summit in December.
As part of the rallying behind the government, 32 Tory MPs have put their
signatures to a letter in today's Times newspaper.
It expresses fierce opposition to the anti-Maastricht stance of some of
their colleagues who represent only 10 per cent of the party they say, but
whose stance is 'undermining the position and policy of the Government and
the standing of the Prime Minister. This plays directly into the hands of
the Opposition and does Great Britain considerable damage'.
Further loyalist letters are being prepared for publication, and
parliamentary motions in support of Maastricht are likely to be tabled.
Ministers themselves have intensified their efforts to persuade. Mr Douglas
Hurd, the foreign secretary, yesterday saw three groups of 'soft Euro-phobe'
MPs, to bring them round behind the government, and to encourage them to be
more vocal in highlighting the benefits of the agreement.
Leading loyalists have now begun queueing up to enter the broadcasting
studios and contest the assertions of the Euro-sceptics.
Sir Michael Grylls, the chairman of the Tory backbench trade and industry
committee, said that the prime minister's stance on Maastricht 'has been
vindicated by the Danish decision to press towards ratification. It fulfils
John Major's pledge in July to bring the Bill back to the Commons when the
Danes had clarified their intentions.
'No one, from whatever party, can now argue that there is any reason for
further indefinite postponement.'
He went on to emphasise the importance of the single market for the
prospects of British economic recovery, a line reinforced by Sir Michael
Angus, president of the CBI. He warned a meeting of Tory backbenchers that
failure to ratify the treaty could cost inward investment and jobs.
</TEXT>
