<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Criminal Justice Bill may be
altered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government yesterday indicated its readiness to amend further the
Criminal Justice Bill following protests from bankers that the bill's
provisions on insider dealing and money laundering could restrict them
unfairly.
Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, said the government
did not want to undermine financial services in London. He said the bill,
which was published on Friday, could be amended to take account of
legitimate concerns.
'I am certainly prepared to listen. I have no interest in imposing on the
City legislation that is going to disrupt legitimate business,' said Mr
Nelson in an interview with the Reuters news agency.
Mr Nelson accepted that the consultation period leading up to the
introduction of the bill last week had been too short to respond to all
concerns. He said the government had faced the threat of infraction
proceedings by the EC.
The latest protests at the bill were made on Monday by the British Bankers'
Association. Lord Inchyra, the director general, said the association was
concerned that senior bankers could inadvertently fall foul of the law.
</TEXT>
