<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Political Notebook: A question of confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE present climate at Westminster it is hazardous to anticipate how Mr
John Major's government will behave during the next few hours, let alone
over the following week.
For the beleaguered prime minister the medium-term now extends to the day
after next. His cabinet sorely lacks a Lord Whitelaw to provide the calm
wisdom which saved Lady Thatcher from so many catastrophes in her early
years as prime minister. So it would be folly to predict with certainty now
the shape and outcome of next week's debate on the Maastricht treaty.
But Downing Street has at last begun to clear away the debris under which it
successfully buried the government over the weekend. The risible threat that
Mr Major would call a snap general election if he lost the vote has been
lifted.
The naive among the prime minister's advisers have realised that while he is
perfectly entitled to stake his own future on a single (and constitutionally
unnecessary) vote, he cannot bind his party, nor his cabinet, to the same
mast.
The conventional wisdom now is that a defeat next week would wound Mr Major
seriously, probably mortally, but somehow the Conservatives would soldier on
in government under a new leader.
Mr Major's colleagues have begun to acknowledge that it is not enough simply
to berate the Euro-sceptics on the Conservative back benches. They have to
win back the hearts if not the minds of a deeply disgruntled but basically
loyal group of Tory MPs whose votes will make the difference between victory
and defeat on Wednesday.
By calling them together for friendly chats in small groups before his
semi-public appeal to the parliamentary party later today at the 1922
Committee, the prime minister has at last started playing to his strengths.
Mr Major wants a substantive motion on Maastricht, one that will demonstrate
to recalcitrant backbenchers that his authority has been restored and to his
EC counterparts that he remains a reliable player in the European game.
Most of his cabinet colleagues share that view. Mr Kenneth Clarke is the
most forceful in arguing for a showdown with the rebels. That has led many
on the right to accuse him of plotting to ensure Mr Major's downfall.
Anyone who has listened to the prime minister's passionate defence of his
European strategy knows that on Maastricht he needs no encouragement from
declared Europhiles.
So the option favoured by most at today's cabinet will be a motion which
faces down the rebels without deliberately inflaming the waverers  - in
spite of the risk that hardened Euro-sceptics will then back a wrecking
Labour amendment.
But the present atmosphere at Westminster - increasingly reminiscent of the
final days of Lady Thatcher - means that outcome cannot be regarded as a
foregone conclusion.
If Mr Richard Ryder announces that his whips will not be able to whittle
down the number of Tory rebels to below 30, Mr Major will be forced into
another retreat and to opt for an adjournment motion. One (pro-European)
cabinet minister has taken to quoting Winston Churchill: 'It is no use
committing suicide if you are going to regret it in later life.'
Against that, Labour's U-turn on Maastricht should encourage the prime
minister to gamble. Many of those Tories who have been threatening to defy
the whips know now they have a qualitatively different decision to make.
There are perhaps a dozen Tory dissidents who could not care less who is in
Downing Street. But the more sophisticated dissidents regard the only
realistic alternatives - Mr Clarke, Mr Michael Heseltine or Mr Douglas Hurd
 -as less acceptable than the present incumbent.
With Mr John Smith ready to shrug off his European credentials in favour of
political opportunism, there will be intense pressure on the Tory side to
maximise Labour's discomfort. The opposition's demand for still further
clarification from Denmark before the legislation can be considered in the
Commons looks as convincing as Downing Street's threat of a general
election.
Mr Smith has accepted that the only way that Labour can credibly vote
against next week's motion is by stating that it has nothing to do with
Europe and everything to do with confidence in the government. But that
means the Conservative party also now has a simple choice: does it have
confidence in its own government?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
