<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Daewoo's chairman may run for election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kim Woo-choong, the chairman of the Daewoo business group, yesterday
indicated that he would accept a possible presidential nomination by South
Korea's newest political party.
But officials of the New Korea party (NPK) remained divided over whether to
offer him the candidancy.
Opponents to Mr Kim's nomination argue that the NPK's chances in the
December election would be hurt if he is the candidate.
There is strong public distrust of Korea's main conglomerates, of which
Daewoo is the fourth largest, because of their close ties with the country's
former military rulers.
However, the NPK, which was formed only a week ago by a conservative
splinter group from the ruling Democratic Liberal party, may have no
alternative but to accept Mr Kim.
Several other potential candidates, including Mr Park Tae-joon, the former
chairman of Pohang Iron and Steel, have refused to become the NPK candidate.
Mr Kim would become the fourth main candidate in the presidential election
if he receives the NPK nomination.
The NPK could play a pivotal role in the forthcoming campaign by helping to
split the conservative vote and possibly delivering the election to Mr Kim
Dae-jung, the leading opposition leader.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10851</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Kenyan poll due after parliament is dissolved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KENYA'S first multi-party elections for 26 years are expected to take place
by mid-December following President Daniel arap Moi's dissolution of
parliament yesterday.
President Moi did not give a date for the poll. Under the constitution
elections must take place within 90 days of a dissolution and the government
must set the date for the elections six weeks in advance of voting.
However, opposition politicians in Nairobi said that they thought it
unlikely that Mr Moi would choose to delay the exercise beyond Christmas.
The ruling Kenya African National Union's (Kanu) main challengers will be
the two wings of the Forum for the Restoration of Democracy (FORD) and the
Democratic party of former vice-president Mr Mwai Kibaki.
The split in FORD was ostensibly over internal party elections, but behind
the dispute lie tribal divisions and personality disputes.
The bickering between the two factions has played into Mr Moi's hands,
eroding FORD's initial popularity and enhancing Kanu's electoral prospects.
Altogether at least 10 parties have been formed and there is little hope
they will unite before the elections.
</TEXT>
