<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Directors fifth in pay league
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIRECTORS' basic pay net of inflation in the UK was the fifth-highest in a
European league for the year to July, according to a survey by Monks
Partnership, the independent remuneration advisers.
The survey covered 1,350 multinational companies in 16 European countries
including the UK and was based on a standard company director post in
subsidiary organisations with annual turnovers of about Pounds 30m.
UK directors' pay increases, at 7.9 per cent for the year to July this year,
were at the upper end of the European league compared with equivalent posts
in multinational subsidiaries across Europe.
The highest basic salary rises recorded were in Portugal, where they
averaged 19.1 per cent, and the lowest in France at 5.8 per cent.
Adjustment for average levels of inflation in each country kept Portuguese
directors at the head of the league with UK increases at 3.6 per cent net of
inflation.
The move towards homogeneity of pay, incentives and benefits among the
senior managements of European international companies was seen to be
gathering pace.
Management Renumeration in Europe. Monks Partnership, Debden Green, Saffron
Walden, Essex CB11 3LX. By subscription.
