FT  29 OCT 92 / Airlines call for monopoly probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK's smaller independent airlines have called on the government to
undertake an urgent review of airline competition and refer the proposed
take-over of Dan-Air by British Airways to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Sir Michael Bishop, chairman of British Midland Airways and Mr Richard
Branson, head of Virgin Atlantic, yesterday pressed their case with the
Office of Fair Trading for a referral to the MMC of BA's acquisition of
Dan-Air.
They also asked for the establishment of a consumer watchdog for the airline
industry called 'Ofair', similar to those already set up for privatised
utilities such as gas, water and electricity.
The OFT is expected to decide in the next 48 hours whether to refer the BA
acquisition to the MMC.
BA warned it would consider pulling out of the deal if faced with long
regulatory hurdles, but the OFT is coming under increasing pressure to refer
the deal.
Sir Michael and Mr Branson said the take-over raised significant issues for
the future of UK airline competition which could not be waved aside for
short term expediency. Sir Michael said that the UK's multi-airline industry
policy 'has never been under greater threat'.
Both chairmen warned that the transaction would result in considerable job
losses in the UK aviation industry, especially at Gatwick, Dan-Air's London
base.
Sir Michael claimed the BA rescue would lead to about 3,000 job losses,
including the 1,600 jobs expected to be shed at Dan-Air and at suppliers.
He argued that more jobs would have been saved if the troubled airline had
collapsed and other carriers had been able to apply for Dan-Air routes out
of Gatwick.
Mr Branson claimed that at least 1,500 jobs would have been saved at Dan-Air
if his earlier rescue proposal had been accepted.
