FT  29 OCT 92 / Yeltsin suppresses parliament guard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin yesterday followed up his ban on the
Communist-nationalist National Salvation Front by suppressing a 5,000-strong
parliamentary guard whose actions have caused disquiet among liberal
legislators.
The guard, formed after last year's failed putsch and answerable directly to
Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the parliamentary speaker, had been accused of
initiating an exchange of fire with the regular militia. On Tuesday, they
were sent to 'guard' the liberal Izvestia newspaper, which Mr Khasbulatov
has insisted must again become the official organ of parliament.
The guard has been withdrawn from Izvestia, but was reported yesterday still
to be in control of the Russian parliamentary building.
The two bans have raised the political tension still further in Moscow,
which is abuzz with rumours of coups, the formation of shadow cabinets and
the imposition of presidential power.
A group of liberally-inclined parliamentary factions yesterday appealed to
Mr Yeltsin not to introduce presidential power.
They argued that 'it would not be a strengthening of presidential power, it
would be an attempt to introduce, through the president, chaos and limitless
authority which would inevitably lead to civil war'.
Mr Khasbulatov, who was reported to have been taken ill last week, has
returned to work this week. His despatch of the guards to Izvestia came
after a decision by both houses of parliament to take back control of the
paper - which has Mr Yeltsin's backing to remain independent.
