<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Waigel snubs Kohl's tax warning: Finance minister insists
rise in 1995 would be 'last resort'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUSSELDORF
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR THEO WAIGEL, the German finance minister, yesterday distanced himself
from Chancellor Helmut Kohl, insisting that a tax rise in 1995 was a 'last
resort' in the struggle to finance German unification and control the public
sector deficit.
He rejected outright any move to increase taxes before then, demanding
further drastic savings measures in the coming weeks to reduce a yawning gap
in government finances, even in 1993.
Mr Kohl also insisted yesterday that there could and would be no tax rises
for two years - in other words, before the 1994 elections - but gave
confusing signals on his willingness to make drastic cuts in state subsidies
to such sensitive sectors as coal-mining, agriculture and ship-building.
Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) closed its annual conference with
an overwhelming vote in favour of a resolution calling for big spending
cuts, increased efforts to boost economic growth in eastern Germany, and tax
rises in 1995. The resolution appeared to be a show of unity, but the party,
and the ruling coalition, remain deeply divided on how to bridge the
spending gap.
Immediate measures are required to trim next year's budget by at least
DM10bn (Pounds 4bn), and probably more like DM15bn, before it comes to the
committee stage in the Bundestag on November 11. First proposals must go to
the cabinet by next Wednesday. A meeting of the parties in the coalition is
scheduled for tonight.
The DM10bn is the saving needed to cope with the loss of revenue expected
from a 1 per cent decline in next year's economic growth rate. In addition,
a string of extra spending plans has been all but agreed to help the
collapsed east German economy, including an increase in investment subsidies
for small businesses.
The central exchequer is likely to face the cost of servicing east Germany's
DM50bn housing debt in 1994 and in 1995 the full burden of DM400bn to
DM500bn of accumulated eastern debts, including the debts of the Treuhand
privatisation agency.
Mr Waigel, who is leader of the Bavaria-based Christian Social Union (CSU)
in the ruling coalition, showed his extreme dislike of the idea of a 1995
tax rise without flatly rejecting it.
'Tax increases only come into consideration as a last resort, when all other
options have been exhausted,' he said,
'What is needed is a painful and unavoidable definition of new priorities.
The room for further borrowing has been played out. Top of the list must
come the exploitation of every possible measure for savings and reordering
of priorities.
'To have tax increases in reserve reduces the pressure to save on both the
central government, and the federal states.'
For his part, Mr Kohl insisted: 'When I say save, I mean save.' But he
underlined the difficulties in cutting subsidies in such areas as
shipbuilding and coal-mining - and flatly rejected the sort of policies
introduced by Mrs Margaret Thatcher in Britain. 'We are a social market
economy, not a market economy.'
</TEXT>
