<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Labour sees EC debate as vote of confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE battleground for next week's crucial debate over Maastricht was staked
out last night as Labour confirmed that it would turn the occasion into a
confidence motion on Mr John Major.
The prime minister led senior cabinet colleagues in an intensive charm
offensive before his important set-piece address to the backbench 1922
committee tonight in a continued effort to whittle down the number of Tory
rebels.
But as government business managers promised a narrow victory next
Wednesday, the big guns of Euro-scepticism - most notably Lady Thatcher -
were sighted in Westminster rallying the undecided to the anti-Maastricht
cause.
A survey of Euro-sceptics conducted by the FT yesterday indicates that as
many as 50 Tory MPs could vote against the government if presented with a
motion calling on them to press ahead with ratification of the Maastricht
treaty. A revolt on this scale would leave the government facing defeat.
But if there is a widely held perception that the vote has become a
confidence motion in which either the government's or the prime minister's
survival are at stake the size of the potential rebellion would shrink
drastically.
Mr Major felt sufficiently confident to predict victory for the first time
yesterday, arguing that Denmark's blueprint for ending the impasse over the
treaty, revealed on Tuesday night, further justified proceeding to
ratification in the UK.
The prime minister's positive tone about the prospects for the Danish
proposals was embarrassingly undermined last night, however, by the leak of
an internal Foreign Office memorandum warning that Danish requirements were
'unlikely to be acceptable to EC member states'.
The paper, written last Friday before Denmark's final proposals were
released, said the UK faces 'a difficult negotiation ahead'. Whitehall
officials said last night that the paper represented 'first thoughts'.
They expressed the view that in the end EC countries would be realistic
enough to accept anything short of renegotiation of the treaty.
Earlier in the day, Mr Major's claimed justification for proceeding was
unanimously rejected by Labour's shadow cabinet who voted to oppose any
motion tabled by the government.
They said that criteria laid out by the prime minister in September for
resuming the ratification process - including European Community agreement
on how Denmark might proceed - had still not been met.
Broadening the context of the debate beyond the timing of ratification, Mr
John Smith, the Labour leader, insisted that the key issue now centred on
'the nature and style of the prime minister's conduct of government'.
The Liberal Democrats, however, decided to vote with the government if the
motion was specifically related to Maastricht.
Mr Major's upbeat victory forecast reflected undisguised relief within the
government that the Danes had clarified their position.
Labour's hardline tactics in insisting that the debate amounted to a vote of
confidence was also thought likely to drive some waverers back into the
government camp.
But the outbreak of optimism among Tory loyalists was tempered by the
immediate call from the Euro-sceptics - rejected by Downing Street - for
Britain also to adopt the Danes' demands, before ratification procedures in
the Commons were resumed.
The Euro-sceptic offensive was boosted from the House of Lords by Lady
Thatcher, who told friendly MPs that she had felt obliged to abandon her
self-imposed decision not to interfere with the Commons.
She was reported to be urging Conservative waverers not to join the 'roll of
shame' of those voting to proceed with the ratification process.
