<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / (CORRECTED) Lloyd's drafts in help from outsiders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 30th October 1992) appended to this article.
THREE consultancy teams are working on initiatives to resolve some of the
most pressing problems at Lloyd's, the insurance market. All have been
appointed within the last few weeks by Mr Peter Middleton, Lloyd's new chief
executive.
Mercer Consulting, management consultants, has been invited to develop
proposals to resolve the problem of 'open years', which occur when
syndicates are unable to close their accounts due to uncertainty over future
claims. Names - the individuals whose assets support underwriting on the
market - who are members of syndicates with open years are unable to leave
the market. The number of syndicates with open years rose sharply this year.
Mr William Knight, of solicitors Simmons and Simmons, and LEK, the
consultants, are to examine how errors and omissions insurers - which cover
businesses on the market against legal awards for negligence - might aid an
out-of-court settlement of litigation between Names and their agents. New
litigation between the two groups is possible following the completion of
recent investigations into the losses at syndicates managed by Gooda Walker
and Feltrim agencies.
Another consultancy firm, First Consulting, is conducting a review of
operations at the Lloyd's Corporation, which provides administration and
marketing services for the market as a whole. Mr Middleton is keen to
improve the corporation's efficiency.
Both the Mercer Fraser team and Mr Knight will work alongside committees of
Names, chosen for their business experience. Mr Middleton and Mr Neil Shaw,
chairman of the Association of Lloyd's Members, are writing this week to
potential members. They are hopeful that the consultants can complete their
work before the end of the year. First Consulting is expected to report
within the next few weeks.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the US credit rating agency, yesterday launched a ranking
service for Lloyd's syndicates. Syndicate Stability Rankings awards one, two
or three stars to syndicates according to their financial stability. The
rankings take into account the syndicates' reported results for the last
four years.
CORRECTION
In a story headlined 'Lloyd's drafts in help from outsiders' in yesterday's
FT, reference was made to Mercer Consulting and Mercer Fraser. Both
references should have been to Mercer Management Consulting. We apologise
for the error.
</TEXT>
