<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: Credit Suisse mounts rescue of
Ekobank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CREDIT SUISSE, Switzerland's third-largest bank, has rescued EKO
Hypothekar-und Handelsbank (Ekobank), one of the country's largest regional
banks.
Ekobank was ordered closed by the Swiss Federal Banking Commission last
Thursday but, following approval of the takeover by its shareholders on
Monday, its branches opened as Credit Suisse branches on Tuesday.
The takeover occurred in the context of a safety net established a year ago
by the Swiss Bankers' Association following the collapse of another regional
bank, Spar und Leihkasse Thun. The intention was to prevent another incident
that would harm the international image of Swiss banks.
Credit Suisse said: 'We are willing and eager to do our part to maintain the
rep-utation of the Swiss financial centre.'
Ekobank, based in Olten, had assets of SFr1.6bn (Dollars 1.1bn) at the end
of 1991, and employs about 100 people. It was owned, and its assets and
liabilities were totally guaranteed, by the local community. As part of the
takeover agreement, the potential liability of the community for future
losses is limited to SFr40m.
Credit Suisse said that provisions for Ekobank's bad loans were made as part
of the agreement on the takeover conditions, and it anticipated that no
further provisions would be necessary.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
