<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Sweden to reform welfare system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWEDEN'S centre-right coalition government is preparing a far-reaching
programme to transform the country's famous cradle-to-grave welfare state by
exposing it to market forces and reducing the financial burden on the
taxpayer.
Mr Carl Bildt, the country's conservative prime minister, said he wanted to
create a 'welfare market'.
Full details of the wide-ranging plans are expected later next month as part
of a government 'convergence' strategy designed to bring Sweden in line with
the standards of the European Community, which it hopes to join at the start
of 1995.
The drive for greater freedom of choice in public services through an
extension of private initiatives will be extended across the entire Swedish
public sector.
Mr Bildt is extremely worried about the growing size of the government's
budget deficit, set to rise to around 10 per cent of Sweden's gross national
product by 1994. Nearly half the government's spending goes on its welfare
programmes.
Around 60 per cent of the country's gross national product is devoted to
public expenditure, the highest proportion of any country in the world. This
will be reduced in stages closer to the current EC average of around 46 per
cent.
The sweeping plans can be expected to arouse considerable resistance inside
Sweden's huge public services sector, especially from the trade unions.
However, a consensus has been developing across the political spectrum that
accepts the need to break-up the traditional bureaucratic system and
introduce greater efficiency with more choice for people and the contracting
out to the private sector - often in the form of co-operatives - of some
services.
</TEXT>
