<TEXT>
XEROX, the document processing group, yesterday reported an 11 per cent
increase in third-quarter net income and announced a Dollars 444m provision
for restructuring at Crum and Forster, its property/casualty insurance unit.
The provision was offset by the realisation of Dollars 444m in capital gains
at Crum and Forster, but the subsidiary warned it expected to take extra
provisions in the fourth quarter.
Xerox shares fell Dollars 2 1/4 to close at Dollars 76 as analysts expressed
disappointment over the results of its core copier business and concern as
to whether Crum and Forster's remaining unrealised capital gains would be
sufficient to cover any further provisions.
Xerox reported net income of Dollars 135m, or Dollars 1.18 a share, compared
to Dollars 121m, or Dollars 1.06, in the same period of last year, while
revenues rose to Dollars 4.5bn from Dollars 4.3bn. Analysts expectations had
centred on earning per share of about Dollars 1.29.
For the nine months, it produced net income 11 per cent higher at Dollars
402m, or Dollars 3.53 a share, compared to Dollars 363m, or Dollars 3.18.
Revenues were Dollars 13.1bn, against Dollars 12.9bn.
Mr Paul Allaire, chairman, said the company's new range of document
processing machines were 'meeting with excellent customer reception, despite
the weak economic environment in the US and deteriorating economies in
Europe, Japan and Brazil'.
Third-quarter income from the document processing side was 10 per cent ahead
at Dollars 128m, while revenues grew 9 per cent to Dollars 3.6bn. Excluding
currency effects, revenues grew 4 per cent.
Mr Stuart Ross, chairman of the financial services business, said a new
management team at Crum and Forster was looking at several alternatives for
restructuring its insurance operations and strengthening its financial
position.
