FT  28 OCT 92 / Army contract goes to Saab
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 40M CONTRACT to provide the British Army with laser equipment to
simulate firing has been awarded to the Saab group of Sweden.
Saab was chosen in preference to Loral Solartron, a subsidiary of the US
Loral group, which provides similar equipment for US forces.
Royal Ordnance, the British Aerospace subsidiary, and GEC-Marconi, offering
a French system, were both eliminated at an earlier stage of the
competition. However, Royal Ordnance is expected to supply small-arms
training equipment under the Saab contract.
The equipment is designed to reduce the amount of live firing carried out by
troops in training. The Ministry of Defence said it would bring 'cost
savings and benefits for the environment'.
The project involves laser projectors attached to a range of weapons
including tanks, anti-tank missiles and guns. Each 'hit' is recorded by
receivers carried by individual troops or vehicles. Options for extra
realism include sound effects and puffs of smoke.
Battlefield exchanges during exercises can subsequently be replayed and
performance analysed.
