FT  28 OCT 92 / Tourism fails language test
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONLY a third of companies dealing with foreign tourists can cope fully with
customers' language needs, according to a survey for the British Tourist
Authority and the Department of Employment, Michael Skapinker writes.
Although more than 90 per cent of the companies responding to the survey
said their staff came into contact with native speakers of other languages,
63 per cent relied to at least some extent on customers being able to speak
English.
The tourist authority said the survey, conducted by the Institute of
Manpower Studies, may have presented too optimistic a picture. A total of
1,500 companies were sent the questionnaire and 29.4 per cent responded. The
authority said companies with a commitment to foreign language skills were
more likely to have responded.
Although 70 per cent of respondents said their language needs would
increase, only 45 per cent planned to step up training.
