<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Whips weigh their carrots and
sticks - How Tory party managers will try to pull MPs into line over Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's counter-offensive against Tory Euro-sceptics was under way
last night, orchestrated by party whips trained in persuasion techniques
ranging from the subtle and gentlemanly to the blunt and unforgiving.
Mr John Major will take the rare step of addressing the 1922 committee of
backbench MPs tomorrow - he usually appears only a few times a year. He met
about a dozen wavering MPs in his Commons office yesterday.
Other Conservatives have been offered face-to-face meetings with Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, or Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, foreign
office minister. Behind the scenes, the 14 government whips have begun to
calculate the possible outcomes when the Commons debates Maastricht next
week.
Until last night, it had been mostly a listening exercise - in contrast with
the tactics of the Euro-rebels who have already begun to flood backbenchers'
meetings and press colleagues to take sides.
Cabinet ministers meet tomorrow morning, before Mr Major addresses
backbenchers, to agree next week's motion. They will want a report from Mr
Richard Ryder, the chief whip, on the likely extent of opposition.
Attempts to head off a defeat are likely to escalate dramatically as the
vote approaches. There will be fewer offers of carrots, more use of the
stick. Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, is abroad until the weekend but
could join government attempts to quell the revolt over the weekend.
Whips, by tradition, pride themselves in knowing what the result of a vote
will be and, if defeat looks certain, in trying to ensure the government
swerves to minimise damage. Last week's climbdown over pit closures, albeit
ungraceful and hurried, is a textbook example.
Mr Ryder, working from an office off the members' lobby and rarely seen by
the public except occasionally in television shots, has a range of weapons
to use.
For younger MPs there will be grave warnings about future ministerial career
prospects. For others there will be appeal to loyalty, reminders of past
favours or hints about positions on the Commons select committees - though
some Euro-sceptics have already lost theirs.
Some Euro-rebels believe the next tactic will be to contact MPs'
constituency assoc-iations, alerting local officers of the trouble their
member is causing.
'We know it's going to be a tough game,' said one leading Euro-sceptic, as
if bracing himself for the battle ahead.
One - unlikely - option for Mr Major would be a television address, to
appeal over MPs heads to constituents. That might give the impression of
panic. A series of television interviews, which can be arranged with only a
few hours notice, is an alternative.
Whips' techniques vary. Some are civilised, merely politely inquiring into
an MP's intentions and offering to help answer points of concern.
Mr Ryder is amiable but firm. Mr David Lightbown, the large-framed assistant
whip, sometimes intimidates waverers with his gruff voice and burly
presence.
Each whip oversees a group of MPs, acting as a conduit for the passing on of
views and voting intentions. Different MPs require different techniques. 'If
you talk to a school teacher about how they treat their children, you will
see that they don't use the same method on each of them,' explained one.
Heavy-handed techniques can backfire. Mr Walter Sweeney, Tory MP for Vale of
Glamorgan, says he was told before the summer recess that he would be
'making life difficult' if he signed a Commons motion tabled by
Euro-sceptics.
He backed off then but has since told whips in a letter that he will vote
against the government when the Commons debates a substantive motion on
Maastricht.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
