FT  28 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Accounts body calls for reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTING standard dealing with deferred taxation should be amended to
improve the level of disclosure, the Institute of Chartered Accountants of
Scotland said yesterday.
The analysis of SSAP 15, an accounting statement introduced in 1978, was
edited by Professor Pauline Weetman of the University of Stirling on behalf
of the research committee of the Scottish institute.
Deferred tax is that amount assessed for tax purposes in one period but
recognised in a company's financial statements in another.
In the long term the study calls for a 'flow-through' approach to accounting
for tax, in which actual tax charges would be adjusted only for short-term
timing differences such as those caused by interest payable or receivable
being different to that paid or received.
In the short term, it suggests:
A new disclosure note reconciling the effective tax charge to that which
would have applied at the full rate of corporation tax.
Greater emphasis in the standard on the need for better quality disclosure
in the notes to the accounts.
Treating advance corporation tax as a separate asset item which should not
be set against the deferred tax liability.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
