<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Straw attacks homes 'crisis'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday launched a five-point plan designed to end Britain's
'biggest housing crisis since the war'.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, accused the government of
'perverse economics' in preventing local authorities from using their own
funds to help solve the shortage of accommodation.
He called for:
The government to use empty repossessed houses for homeless families;
Court orders for repossessions to be refused until the lenders offered
practical help and advice to people in arrears, with options of accepting
reduced payments for a limited period;
The government to ensure that mortgage rescue schemes, which had so far
failed, could be made to work towards helping those owners in difficulties
remain in their homes as tenants;
The introduction of effective shared ownership schemes involving the payment
of lower mortgages in return for giving the lender or housing association an
equity share in the home;
An end to constraints on local authorities using capital receipts worth
Pounds 5bn.
Mr Straw said: 'The housing market is facing its biggest crisis since the
war. A million people live in homes worth less than they paid for them,
house prices are going through the floor, while repossessions and
homelessness are at unacceptable levels.
'Labour believes that cost-effective measures can be taken to stem
repossessions and to stimulate the market.'
</TEXT>
