<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / World Trade News: EC accuses US of steel 'harassment'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community and other steel exporters yesterday accused US steel
producers of 'trade harassment' in mounting a series of anti-dumping and
anti-subsidy actions.
The 84 petitions by US producers, 38 directed against EC members, were filed
after talks on a multilateral steel accord collapsed, the EC told Gatt's
anti-dumping committee yesterday. The EC urged the US to scrap the actions.
The suits, involving 21 countries, had been filed though no increase in
steel exports to the US had occurred, and prices of EC steel were higher
than US producers', the EC said. About 2m tonnes of EC steel exports worth
Dollars 800m (Pounds 490.7m) a year were affected by the petitions.
The US was using its anti-dumping procedures to harass foreign competitors,
the EC claimed. It questioned if methods being used to assess dumping were
in line with Gatt's anti-dumping code. But under Gatt rules, the US action
cannot be legally challenged until duties are definitively imposed. The
complaints were echoed by other steel exporters, including Japan, Brazil and
Mexico.
</TEXT>
