<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Europe hopes rise for Gatt breakthrough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER, NANCY DUNNE and IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN hopes of a final breakthrough in the Uruguay Round of world trade
talks were rekindled last night after the US signalled to the European
Community it was prepared to look at new ways to resolve the oilseeds row.
Chances of a deal had virtually collapsed at 2am yesterday, after Mr Ray
MacSharry, EC agriculture commissioner, told Mr Ed Madigan, US agriculture
secretary, he could settle the oilseeds row only inside the framework of
reform of the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) agreed unanimously by the EC
this summer. Mr Madigan said this would be insufficient to satisfy the US
soyabean lobby, and there was nothing further to discuss.
But later Mr Madigan contacted the EC side to indicate US willingness to
offer new oilseeds proposals.
Mr Madigan and Mr MacSharry are now expected to meet in the US this week to
try for political agreement on the Uruguay Round.
At the same time, however, Ms Carol Brookins, a US agriculture consultant
with close ties to the administration, cautioned that Mr Madigan would not
meet Mr MacSharry unless there was a possibility of substantial progress.
Yesterday's development offered the first clear sign of a deal. 'We are
continuing to negotiate for a solution politically acceptable to both of
us,' Mr MacSharry and Mr Madigan stated.
Mr Frans Andriessen, EC external affairs commissioner, was convinced a farm
deal was in reach.
This would pave the way for reform in the 15 trade sectors that the
108-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) has been
negotiating for six years.
Failure could unleash a trade war, with the US threatening punitive tariffs
on EC food exports and the EC retaliating. Yesterday the US seemed ready to
delay sanctions, but Ms Brookins said President George Bush had merely
delayed the move until after the US elections because he did not want to be
seen as acting just for electoral reasons.
The US wants the EC to cut its subsidised oilseeds output to 9m tonnes this
year. Mr MacSharry says the EC can deliver only what is in the CAP reform -
the price and production cuts now Community law.
Ivor Owen, Parliamentary Correspondent, adds: Prime Minister John Major
confirmed that in the last few days he had been in close touch with other
leaders in the EC and the US to urge early resumption of the Gatt talks.
The two sides were in touch and the US was 'holding off from taking trade
retaliation', he said.
</TEXT>
