<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hungarian trade figures released yesterday demonstrated export resilience in
the face of the international economic slowdown, reports Nicholas Denton in
Budapest.
Exports rose 12.5 per cent in the first three-quarters of 1992 compared with
a year earlier, while imports fell back 2 per cent, leaving trade in
balance. Deliveries slowed over the year as Germany, Hungary's largest
trading partner, lost economic momentum. Nevertheless, the Hungarian
government hopes that exports will lift the the economy in 1993.
