FT  28 OCT 92 / Major ready to take on Tory Euro-sceptics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday signalled his readiness to face down his
Euro-sceptic opponents on Maastricht with an unprecedented move to set out
his case personally to all Conservative backbench MPs tomorrow.
However, he used a private meeting last night with a small group of Tory MPs
to play down speculation that he will call a general election if defeated
over the treaty.
The meeting marked the beginning of a concerted government operation to head
off the threatened Conservative revolt in next week's Europe debate.
It followed a public warning by Mr Major to Tory MPs against 'isolating
ourselves' and of losing influence in the European Community.
Mr Major's decision to address tomorrow a full meeting of the 1922 committee
 -the group that embraces all Tory backbenchers - was clearly intended to
underline the prime minister's seriousness about pressing on with the
Maastricht bill.
Last night he was helped by pro-Europe Tory MPs agreeing to campaign more
actively in support of the cabinet line.
He will also be encouraged by Denmark's move to overcome the country's
referendum result on Maastricht. It will weaken his opponents argument that
he should wait until the Danes move before proceeding with the treaty's
ratification.
But amid a feverish atmosphere at Westminster, rightwing Tories were
intensifying attacks on Mr Kenneth Clarke, the pro-Europe home secretary -
accusing him of manoeuvering the prime minister into ratifying Maastricht
with unnecessary speed.
Earlier, senior cabinet ministers and government business managers met to
discuss how to proceed towards next Wednesday's crucial paving debate.
Downing Street officials said that no conclusions had been reached over how
to phrase the motion for debate or on what shape it might take. A decision
will be taken by the full cabinet at its weekly meeting tomorrow.
Nonetheless, senior ministers involved in the talks appear to have backed
what is believed to be Mr Major's preference for a substantive motion,
rather than draw back from a head-on confrontation with the Euro-sceptics by
tabling a technical 'adjournment' motion.
In the Commons, Mr Major appeared to press his personal commitment to
ratification and to castigate opposition parties for threatening to oppose a
paving motion.
His rigorous rebuff was paralleled by Mr Hurd who used a speech to the
European Parliament in Strasbourg to challenge Labour's European
credentials.
Mr Hurd said the opposition's promise to vote against the government next
week indicated a 'change for the worse' in its attitude.
