<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / UK schools at bottom of class
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITONS will be the waiters, porters, cleaners and lavatory attendants of
Europe unless their schools improve, a leading independent school headmaster
warned yesterday.
Speaking in Rouen, France, to the Independent Schools Association, Mr Peter
Owen, its chairman, called for urgent reforms to stop Britain dropping
further behind its continental rivals.
'Who will be the manual workers of the coming decades?' he asked. 'Unless we
act positively, it will be the children passing through British schools
now.' He said Britain's education system was 'woefully inadequate' for most
children, failing to stimulate them or provide adequate qualifications.
Mr Owen, head of Rushmoor School, Bedford, said UK education was 'in crisis'
because of low staying-on rates, poor vocational training, high failure
rates at A-level and weaknesses in language teaching. His conclusions on
language are borne out by a survey of UK companies dealing with foreign
tourists which found that only one-third are equipped to deal with
customers' language requirements.
In the single market, Mr Owen said, if a British job vacancy was advertised
across Europe, at least half the applications would come from foreigners
with fluent English and technical and managerial qualifications.
'The British applicants perhaps left school at 16, or at 18, with poor
results,' he said. 'They have no other qualifications, but have picked up a
little varied experience at the times when they have been in work.'
The ISA's Rouen conference has followed a recent pattern of independent
school heads decamping to the continent to laud 'Europe 1992' and lament the
crisis in British education.
