<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / DTI energy-policy chief switches jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE civil servant responsible for overseeing the government's energy policy
has been moved to a new post following last week's row over pit closures,
the Department of Trade and Industry said last night.
But the department denied that Mr Robert Priddle, a deputy secretary at the
DTI, was taking the blame - rather than ministers - for the political
embarrasment faced by the government when it was forced to backtrack over
the proposals in the face of a Tory revolt.
Mr Priddle has switched jobs with the head of the department's corporate and
consumer affairs division - a job of equal rank.
The DTI said it had been decided that, with the government committed to
reviewing the pit closure programme, it was time for a 'fresh pair of hands'
overseeing energy policy. Asked if Mr Priddle was being moved because of his
performance in the job, the DTI said: 'We do not see it in that light.'
By convention, civil servants are rarely blamed for policy failures.
</TEXT>
