<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Britain isolated over HDTV plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK has become increasingly isolated among European Community members in
the debate over the EC's proposed subsidy to television broadcasters for the
development of a European high definition television standard.
Most members are reported to be moving closer to finalising a plan for Ecu
850m (Pounds 680m) in subsidies to help broadcasters in the transit-ion from
conventional to high definition broadcast-ing.
Agreement on most aspects of the plan, apart from the most contentious issue
of the level of the proposed subsidy, is expected within the next few days.
Such agreement paves the way for discussions at a forthcoming meeting of
European telecommunications ministers in Brussels next month to focus on the
issue of the level of subsidy.
The UK, however, is opposed to any subsidy and is in the minority on this
issue, in spite of its presidency of the Community.
At a meeting of the EC's Telecommunications Council in June, the UK opposed
the EC's proposal for a subsidy to broadcasters of Ecu 850m as 'totally
unacceptable'.
'We will oppose any expenditure until we see . . . a convincing business
case (for a subsidy),' Mr Edward Leigh, the technology minister, said at the
time.
That business case was put forward in the form of a report prepared for the
commission which was on the whole favourably received by member countries.
While the level of subsidy is likely to be a source of debate among member
countries, the UK appears to be alone in remaining fundament-ally opposed to
the sub-sidy.
'We are working on coming up with a response to the commission's study,' a
spokesman for the Department of Trade and Industry said.
Meanwhile, a consortium including Dixons, the electrical retailer, Sony, the
consumer electronics manufacturer, and BSkyB, the satellite broadcaster, has
proposed a lower level of subsidy to broadcasters which could be a
compromise solut-ion.
However, a level of subsidy significantly lower than the proposed Ecu 850m
is unlikely to achieve the objective of the commission's action plan to
create a critical mass of broadcasts to stimulate the market for high
definition TV.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
