<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Doubts over market in health care
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S health care reforms are failing to create an internal
market as planned, according to a survey from accountants Arthur Andersen
released yesterday.
Nearly 80 per cent of hospital chief executives and unit general managers
did not believe the National Health Service objective of creating an
internal market is being achieved.
More than 70 per cent, however, said the reforms had resulted in
improvements in overall efficiency, quality of service, average length of
occupancy and waiting lists.
The survey questioned senior executives from 50 hospitals across England in
July, and spanned those from existing trusts, non-trusts and units applying
for trust status.
About 70 per cent said that community relations had remained the same or
worsened since the reforms, and a third said staff morale had deteriorated.
The most significant problems in implementing the reforms included the
adequacy of information, the timetable established, relationships with
purchasers, quality of management and internal resistance. The survey
suggested there was less sharing of information with other hospitals than in
the past.
Only just over a tenth said information systems were adequate for their
needs and there was little consensus over the most appropriate indicators
for monitoring performance.
NHS reforms - Impact and Implications. Arthur Andersen, 1 Surrey St, London
WC2R 2PS.
</TEXT>
