<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Gains tax switch on assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VALUATION of a gift of business assets for capital gains tax purposes
can be deferred until those assets are sold, under a new statement of
practice issued by the Inland Revenue, Andrew Jack writes.
The guidance, numbered SP8/92, applies to taxpayers with shares in an
unquoted, trading company which they or their family control.
As from now it says that claims for gift holdover relief will normally be
accepted automatically by the Revenue, and that valuations may be deferred
until the time when these assets are disposed of.
The voluntary arrangement requires the consent of both the donor and the
recipient of the assets. Anyone can continue to agree valuations and
calculate the gain with the Revenue at the time of the transfer if they
wish.
In practice, capital gains tax liability may be deferred for many years or
may never be incurred because the assets continue to be transferred so there
is never a capital gain.
Holdover relief applies when the recipient of the gift agrees to assume the
full capital gain on the asset which would have accrued to the donor.
Until now, valuations have had to be calculated and agreed with the Revenue
at the time of the transfer.
The Revenue said the new procedures have been introduced in part to reduce
the compliance burden for taxpayers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
