<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Government may cut OECD budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is considering cutting its contributions to the Organisation
for Economic Co-operation and Development - a move which could lead to a
sharp reduction in the organisation's assessment of member countries'
economic performances.
Just over 6 per cent of the OECD's budget comes from the UK. The Foreign
Office - which last year contributed Pounds 5.2m to the OECD - is seeking
support for its reduction from the other 23 members.
If the British move is successful, the budget allotted to the OECD's core
economic activities, including annual surveys of member countries and
twice-yearly economic forecasts, could be reduced.
The proposal comes at a time of Treasury sensitivity about independent
assessments of the UK economy which is still struggling to emerge from its
longest recession for 50 years.
The UK delegation to the OECD said a high value was put on OECD economic
work, but refused to comment on the proposed cuts because discussions on the
overall budget were in progress.
In order to succeed, Britain will have to convince other members that some
of the organisation's economic output is expendable. British representatives
will stress that world and domestic economic conditions are forcing it to
seek cuts in its contributions to all international organisations.
Britain is also anxious to see 'efficiency improvements' which could affect
the organisation's economic studies.
However, some member countries place a higher value than others on the
surveys and forecasts and would be unhappy to see the OECD's economic
activities reduced.
One reason for the UK unease is the possible inclusion of criticism about
the domestic economy in January's annual survey.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
