<TEXT>
USX, the US steel and energy group, yesterday reported third-quarter net
income of Dollars 10m, down from Dollars 28m a year ago, amid weak markets
for steel and refined oil products, and announced it was halving the
dividend due to holders of its energy stock.
USX has divided the shares in the consolidated group into two separate
issues which track the fortunes of its Marathon oil business and its US
Steel subsidiary.
Mr Charles Corry, the chairman, said the dividend on Marathon stock had been
cut from 35 cents to 17 cents 'to maintain financial strength and
flexibility' while continuing to invest heavily in projects which were
expected to enhance its production profile from late-1993.
'Marathon group's profitability and cash-flow have been negatively affected
by depressed refined product margins in 1992,' he added. These stemmed
mainly from low petroleum product price levels relative to crude oil.
The group also announced it would adopt two new accounting standards in the
fourth quarter - FAS 106 and FAS 109 - and would restate its first-quarter
figures to account for these non-cash items. US Steel's income would be
reduced by around Dollars 1.2bn and Marathon's by some Dollars 275m to
Dollars 375m.
Marathon reported third-quarter net income of Dollars 17m, or 5 cents a
share, compared to Dollars 23m, or 8 cents, in the third quarter of last
year. Sales were Dollars 3.4bn, compared to Dollars 3.5bn before. US Steel
reported a net loss of Dollars 7m, or 13 cents a share, compared to net
income of Dollars 5m, or 9 cents a share, on sales unchanged at Dollars
1.3bn.
The figures were dragged down by start-up costs for the new slab caster at
the company's Mon Valley Works, near Pittsburgh, and weak markets for
tubular products. Prices remained stable but at levels below the same period
of 1991.
