<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHEVRON, one of the biggest US oil and gas groups, yesterday reported a 21
per cent rise in third-quarter net earnings to Dollars 378m, or Dollars 1.11
a share, compared with Dollars 313m, or 90 cents, a year ago.
Stripping out special items and foreign exchange in both years, Chevron said
earnings doubled to Dollars 419m, or Dollars 1.23, from Dollars 210, or 60
cents. Revenues advanced 11 per cent to Dollars 11.1bn, from Dollars 10bn.
Chevron, like its competitors, said earnings were boosted by higher prices
for crude oil, US natural gas and US refined product.
The results were helped by reorganisation and cost-cutting, which
contributed to an 11 per cent reduction in operating expenses from last
year's third quarter.
The weak economy, however, took a toll on profits from Chevron's chemicals
business and international refining and marketing. Domestic petroleum
operations were hurt by Hurricane Andrew, which disrupted production in
August and September.
Mr Ken Derr, chairman and chief executive, said fourth-quarter results would
include further cost reductions. The company also expects an after-tax gain
of about Dollars 375m from the stock-for-property swap with Penzoil.
During the quarter, US exploration and production profits soared to Dollars
253m, including gains of Dollars 62m from special items, from only Dollars
29m last year, including one-time gains of Dollars 10m. Chevron's average
crude oil sales price rose 99 cents a barrel to Dollars 17.94, while average
natural gas prices climbed 40 per cent to Dollars 1.75 per thousand cubic
feet.
Refining and marketing brought in earnings of Dollars 73m, including
one-time charges of Dollars 21m, compared with a loss of Dollars 10m a year
earlier, which included environmental provisions of Dollars 53m.
Chevron's chemicals business lost Dollars 7m in the quarter compared with
earnings of Dollars 44m last year. International refining and marketing lost
Dollars 4m in the quarter, compared with profits of Dollars 136m, which
included a favourable tax adjustment of Dollars 62m.
