<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / International Company News: SC Johnson to acquire Drackett
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRISTOL-MYERS Squibb, the world's third-biggest pharmaceuticals company, is
selling its Drackett household product business for Dollars 1.15bn in cash
to SC Johnson &amp; Son, a privately-held consumer products company.
Bristol-Myers announced in July it intended to sell Drackett in a move to
sharpen its competitive edge in the drugs industry.
Drackett contributed about Dollars 600m to Bristol-Myers's Dollars 11.2bn
1991 sales. Analysts had expected the business to fetch about Dollars 1bn to
Dollars 1.25bn.
On Wall Street, shares in Bristol-Myers rose Dollars  1/2 to close at
Dollars 66 5/8 but disappointment with its performance this year has driven
the company's share price down from a 52-week high of Dollars 90 1/8 .
Bristol-Myers's place in the changing pharmaceuticals market is unclear. The
company reported profits growth of only 5 per cent in the first nine months
of this year, against Merck's 17 per cent improvement in the same period.
The disposal of Drackett is an important step as the company increases its
focus on health care.
Mr Viren Mehta, partner at Mehta and Isaly in New York, said: 'Drugs
companies need to be able to maintain a high-risk high-profit
pharmaceuticals business. The Drackett sale will free up the management
resources to concentrate on pharmaceuticals.'
Drackett's products, including Windex and Drano, have a strong presence in
the consumer products market, but sales for the business have been flat to
lower this year, and its marketing costs are high.
The Drackett sale leaves Clairol as Bristol-Myers's largest
non-pharmaceuticals business. Mr Mehta expects the company eventually to
divest Clairol, 'but Bristol-Myers management comes from Clairol and there's
probably a sentimental attachment to it.'
Bristol-Myers expects to record a substantial special gain once the sale of
Drackett is completed.
The Drackett acquisition will strengthen SC Johnson's position in the
home-care industry. The company has annual sales of about Dollars 3.3bn. Its
products include Pledge, Shout and Raid. SC Johnson plans to divest
Drackett's consumer furniture care and air freshener brands, which are
product lines where it already has a strong market presence.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the US ratings agency, yesterday cut its ratings on SC
Johnson's commercial paper and senior debentures to reflect the additional
debt to cover the purchase.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
