<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 92 / Babcock group offers Pounds 267m Rosyth guarantee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CONSORTIUM led by the Babcock International engineering group is offering
to underwrite a Pounds 267m project to complete work on new submarine docks
at Rosyth in Scotland, in an effort to save the dockyard.
The guarantee by Babcock, Wimpey Construction and NNC, a subsidiary of
General Electric Company of the UK, means that they would carry
responsibility for any cost overruns.
Babcock International has a 65 per cent interest, alongside Thorn EMI, in
the company which has been operating the state-owned Rosyth Royal Dockyard
since 1987.
It is fighting to prevent its work on nuclear-powered submarines being moved
to the Devonport yard at Plymouth. Rosyth managers have said that if that
happened the yard, which employs 4,000 people, would face closure.
Up to now Rosyth has carried out all refitting and refuelling of Britain's
Polaris ballistic-missile submarines. Work on other nuclear-powered
submarines has been split between the yards.
Construction of the new facility at Rosyth began five years ago in order to
provide a dock big enough for the Trident submarines which will replace the
Polaris boats. The Pounds 267m would be in addition to more than Pounds 120m
already spent on the project.
DML, Devonport's operator, is bidding to take over all the submarine work
with a rival project that it says could be completed for Pounds 170m.
Babcock, however, claims that the Devonport project, based on adapting
70-year-old docks to meet nuclear safety requirements, could prove much more
expensive than planned.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
