<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 92 / International Company News: Inco cuts pay-out to 10 cents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE sliding price of nickel has led Inco, the western world's largest
producer, to slash its dividend by more than half, despite reporting higher
third-quarter earnings.
Inco said yesterday that it had cut its dividend from 25 US cents to 10
cents. The Toronto-based company has already announced production cuts and
other austerity measures, and said yesterday that additional steps may be
taken.
Third-quarter earnings rose to USDollars 10.6m, or 9 cents a share, from
Dollars 4.5m, or 3 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenues dropped to
Dollars 607.4m from Dollars 663.6m. The latest figures include an Dollars
18.8m charge to cover the cost of voluntary retirements at the company's
Sudbury operations in Ontario.
Nickel prices realised during the third quarter slipped to Dollars 3.47 a
pound from Dollars 3.90 a year earlier. But this was offset by a sharp drop
in the cost of sales and operating expenses, from Dollars 560m to Dollars
488m, and a slight improvement in copper and cobalt prices.
Deliveries of nickel were almost unchanged at 112m lb in the third quarter
while shipments of copper rose from 40m to 44m lb. But Inco said part of the
improvement in third-quarter earnings was due to higher deliveries of metal
produced at its own facilities.
Inco blamed a sharp rise in Russian exports and the delayed recovery in
major industrial economies for the sinking nickel market. The London Metal
Exchange three-month price has tumbled further since the end of the third
quarter and is now only slightly above Dollars 2 per lb.
</TEXT>
