<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Berisford winds up its coffee trading
associate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BERISFORD International, the property and commodities group, announced an
agreement that will result in the winding up of Rayner Coffee International
(RCI), its 45 per cent-owned coffee trading associate.
Berisford, which nearly went into receivership in 1990, is now little more
than a shell, with its businesses reduced to a UK property portfolio and
some small agribusinesses in California.
Having dealt with RCI, the group wants to build a new core business through
acquisitions in the services and manufacturing sectors. It is interested in
the US, where it has considerable unused tax losses.
Berisford said a programme of asset sales had reduced its obligation to RCI
from Dollars 115m (Pounds 70.5m) in September last year to Dollars 45m. The
group agreed to pay RCI's bankers Dollars 45m by March 31 next year.
Berisford said its restructuring would cap its financial obligations to RCI
and eliminate guarantees to RCI.
Berisford is paying RCI Dollars 26m for assets where it expects some further
limited recovery in the long term. The amount will be set against secured
debt owed by RCI to Berisford.
Having reached this agreement, RCI's directors have asked Berisford, as the
only secured and largest unsecured creditor, to petition for the winding up
of RCI. Berisford said the impact of these events was covered by provisions
in its accounts.
Berisford said it had realised Pounds 21m from asset sales since March this
year and expected to generate sufficient funds from other agreed and planned
disposals to achieve a positive net cash position during the current
financial year, in spite of the repayment of the Dollars 45m by its year-end
on March 31.
Mr Alan Bowkett, Berisford's chief executive officer, said that while he
regretted the demise of the coffee business, this deal freed Berisford from
the drain imposed on its resources by RCI.
Berisford's shares closed unchanged at 16p, giving the group a market value
of Pounds 79.4m.
</TEXT>
