<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 92 / British Gas to restate results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS has agreed to restate the 1991 figures to be published in its
next set of annual accounts following discussions with the Financial
Reporting Review Panel, the UK's accounting standards watchdog.
The panel ruled that the company's decision to change its year-end from
March 31 to December 31 last year, but then publish its results for the 12
months to December 31 contravened the 1985 Companies Act.
Under section 223 (3) of the act, it should have shown the results only for
the nine months from April 1 to December 31. British Gas has agreed to amend
the comparable figures in its accounts for the current year, which will
reduce 1991 pre-tax profits from Pounds 1.47bn to Pounds 496m.
The panel has agreed to take no further action. It could have forced British
Gas to reissue the last set of accounts, which would have proved costly
since it has more than 2m shareholders.
Mr Nicholas St John, group chief financial accountant at British Gas, said
the company had publicised its decision and shown the nine-month figures in
summary accounts and a note to the full accounts.
He said use of 12-month figures had been approved by its auditors and the US
Securities and Exchange Commission but no comparable process with the panel
before publication was available in the UK.
It wanted to show 12-month figures to reflect the fact that two-thirds of
profits were generated in the first quarter of the year, reflecting the
highly seasonal demand for gas. The panel said it accepted the directors'
assurances that there was no intention to mislead and that the company acted
in good faith.
The decision potentially raises a precedent by which other companies might
argue before the panel that they had contravened accounting regulations but
were not attempting to mislead.
However, Mr Sidney Treadgold, secretary to the panel, said yesterday: 'Each
case is addressed on its merits and no precedents are being set. The panel
felt it right to record the directors' intentions but our criterion must be
conformity with the (companies') acts.'
British Gas changed the year-end as many joint ventures and subsidiaries
account for that period.
</TEXT>
