<TEXT>
Sir, Having spent nearly 10 years as chairman of the financial committee of
a successful local authority, perhaps I could comment on the suggestion that
the taxpayer should compensate the local authorities which lost money with
the Bank of Credit and Commerce International. The higher the return on
money lent, in theory and in practice, the higher the risk; and those
placing the money should have been made aware of that. The particular
circumstances of the largest loser - the Western Isles - gives cause for
concern.
I see no reason why those of us who are prudent should always be expected to
bail out the foolish - if we did, prudence would have no merit.
Jeremy C Kilner,
