FT  27 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is surprisingly little opera on television these days, considering how
popular it is supposed to have become in the last few years. (I suspect too
much significance has been attributed to that single snatch of 'Turandot'
used in the World Cup sig tune, yet opera surely is more popular). But today
brings the real thing: Otello (7.25 BBC2), live from Covent Garden with
Domingo in the title role, Kiri Te Kanawa as Desdemona, and Sergei Leiferkus
making his debut in the role of Iago. The occasion, sponsored by Boeing, is
particularly special since it marks the 80th birthday of Sir Georg Solti who
conducts at the Royal Opera House in the presence of the Prince and Princess
of Wales. The work is sung in Italian with English subtitles. In the
interval (about 8.40) Jeremy Isaacs, director of the Opera House, talks to
Solti about his career.
C4's arts magazine Without Walls (9.00) ends its sequence about sexuality
with Howard Schuman examining claims that DH Lawrence was a homosexual. The
second half is devoted to 1961: the year of the E-type Jaguar. Omnibus
(10.25 BBC1) provides a profile of artist Avigdor Arikha whose work has
progressed from abstract to figurative.
